                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="13555248" author="apurtell" created="Wed, 16 Jan 2013 17:44:11 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I should say pseudorandomized with the ability to set the seed for repeatability. This may be a tall/impossible order. I&apos;m not familiar with JUnit/Surefire internals sufficient.y &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13555273" author="nkeywal" created="Wed, 16 Jan 2013 18:00:28 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I don&apos;t think it&apos;s immediately available.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As far as I know, Surefire has a random order execution, but my understanding is that it&apos;s on a per class basis, so it&apos;s not what we need.&lt;br/&gt;
Withing JUnit, it&apos;s likely possible to do what we want by writing a custom runner, but it&apos;s not available in the core product (it may have been partly implemented, but I&apos;m not sure the seed would be there, even if it is a good point).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The closest stuff I have, from what I understood but not tested, is to use MethodSorters.JVM on a JDK 1.7: it will be random but without seed.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13555279" author="apurtell" created="Wed, 16 Jan 2013 18:04:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=nkeywal&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;nkeywal&quot;&gt;Nicolas Liochon&lt;/a&gt;. I&apos;ll play around with this and if I come up with something useful will post a patch.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13599269" author="enis" created="Mon, 11 Mar 2013 20:48:25 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;+1 on the idea. I&apos;ve also come across some tests which basically fail without prev tests having been executed. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
